reviews.review_text: Amazing Exposition of the Cripe This is an amazing exposition of Jerry on the Stephen Cripe "Lightning Bolt" guitar which possessed the ability to sound as acoustic electric as it sounded electric acoustic.

BTW I remember being at these shows, I think 3 in a row? Always such high energy on the fall tours, BTW rocks the first set and the Bertha closer left me waiting for the second set. Haven't heard this show in years but it sounds great. Thanks for the sharing, just another grateful memory while we go FURTHUR!!

Great show, fantastic recording! This is a wonderful recording of a great, high-energy show.  I was lucky enough to be in attendance so admittedly I couldn't be any more biased, but the fact that parts were broadcast during the GD Hour proves how good it is.  Back when this show happened, the only way that you could get Dead music was ordering it from the Grateful Dead Almanac, from a record store, or if you were lucky enough to know someone who had some tapes (the first Dick's Picks hadn't even been released yet).  When I saw this show I had some of the live and studio albums and had just acquired my very first batch of tapes, but there were still a lot of songs that I didn't know.  Many of the songs played on this night I'd never heard before, but none more notable than Not Fade Away.  The song was great, but I was absolutely blown away by the crowd chanting "You know our love will not fade away" until the band came back out for the encore!  If you can believe it, I thought that this was the first time that it had happened!  The way that the chanting and the clapping bounced and echoed around that big ol' place was amazing!  I would have preferred a different encore, but I would have preferred not to hear Way To Go Home or Corinna either, so you can't always get what you want.  But on this night, we got most of what we wanted and you can't get much better than a Wheel > Watchtower > Attics > NFA to end a second set.
